{
  "texts": [
    "These X. laevis chromosomes display evidence of decaying subtelomeric signatures in the region surrounding the ancestral L-M fusion (Fig. 1 and Supplementary Fig.",
    "Similarly, enrichment of subtelomerically-associated repeats is observed in H. boettgeri chromosome 8_10 (Supplementary Fig. 8c-e) near the junction between the portions of the chromosome with M and J/K ancestry (the J/K fusion occurred near the base of pipids).",
    "In both cases, the centromere from element M (i.e., the centromere in X. tropicalis chromosome 9) is maintained after fusion.",
    "The inversion of the p-arm from chromosome 8S also has evidence of decaying sequence but the median is less than the median Jukes-Cantor (JC) distance at the chromosome 9_10 fusion, suggesting that the fusion preceded the inversion.",
    "The long-range and, in most cases, chromosome-scale collinearity (Supplementary Fig. 7 and Supplementary Table 9) among the frog species we examined, despite a combined branch length of 1.05 billion years (Supplementary Tables 10 and 11), parallels the conserved synteny observed in birds 79 and reptiles 80, but differs from the substantial chromosome variation found in mammals 22, 41."
  ]
}